  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, visceral experience for many students and professionals who see themselves as part of groups historically marginalized in these fields. Growing up in Philadelphia, I've seen firsthand how the weight of stereotypes can shape opportunities, especially for people from backgrounds where STEM isn't the default path. My parents both had limited formal education—my dad finished primary school and my mom got a vocational diploma—so I've always known that academic success isn't guaranteed by family tradition. That's why I'm so invested in understanding how stereotype threat operates. It's when people feel their performance is being judged based on group identity rather than individual ability, which can lead to anxiety and underperformance. In my sales work, I've noticed how similar dynamics play out in everyday interactions: when someone feels they're 'not the right type' for a situation, their confidence dips, and they perform worse. Addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness—it needs systemic change. Schools and workplaces should create environments where everyone feels safe to make mistakes and where success is measured by effort, not just outcomes. For instance, in my community, volunteering with youth programs has shown me how mentorship can help dismantle stereotypes early. We need to normalize conversations about bias without shaming anyone, and provide resources that acknowledge the emotional toll of being in a 'stereotyped' group. It's not about fixing people—it's about fixing systems. And honestly, that's something we can all do, starting with ourselves.",
